solutions.content:
The basic idea is to use a monotonous stack to keep the bars of decreasing height. 

We maintain a stack which is decreasing in "height" value and processing like below: 
Once we encounter an element that's taller than the current stack top element, we know that the stack top element will be a potential "bottom" of the area that can hold water. 

So we pop the top element from the stack. In this case, the next elements in the stack that is greater than the "bottom" element (left bar), as well as the currently checking element (the right bar), will form an area that can hold water.

The capacity formed will be *height x width*, where: 
* heigth = min(left, right) - bottom
* width = right idx -left idx -1


With the example given in the problem description, below image explains what will happen when processing elements with index 6 and 7:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/isaacjumac/image_1571937715.png)


Accepted solution:
```
class Solution {
    public int trap(int[] H) {
        int n = H.length;
        if(n == 0) return 0;
        Stack<Integer> stk = new Stack<>();
        int capacity = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            while(!stk.isEmpty() && H[stk.peek()] < H[i]){
                int low = stk.pop();
                if(!stk.isEmpty()){
                    int depth = Math.min(H[stk.peek()], H[i])-H[low];
                    int width = i-stk.peek()-1;
                    capacity += depth*width;
                } 
            }
            if(stk.isEmpty() || H[stk.peek()] >= H[i]){
                stk.push(i);
            }
        }

        return capacity;
    }
}
```

