# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
First when will the rain water be trapped between to blocks...
case 1 ) When one block is bigger than other with some space in betweem them 

case 2 ) when both blocks are of same size and there is some space between them

Let us consider case 1 with an example[4,2,0,3,2,5] 
For the 1st element i.e 4 
->The left big block is itselt of size 4 && the right biggest block is of size 5
->For now let us ignore all the remaining blocks,The water being trapped between the blocks 4 and 5 will definetely have a height of 4 with some width
->Now let us also consider the remaining blocks between them of size less than left big block and right big block,They are immersed in the rainwater of height 4
->Now difinetely the water above each block is 4 - height of that particular block (For better understanding draw a graph on the paper)

->Now u get the water being trapped between the 4 and 5


-->The same applies for the remaining blocks

For that simply use 2 arrays to store the left biggest boundary and right biggest boundary of each block

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First find the left biggest of each element and store it in an array using for loop

And then find the right biggest of each block and store it in another array using another for loop

Use another for loop to calculate the number of units of rain water trapped between or above each block

count += (minimum(leftblock and right block) - height of the current block)


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)+O(n)+O(n) = O(n)

- Space complexity:
